Abstract

In this research project I aimed to examine how the management of finances in California colleges factors into the obtainment of a degree within the California student body as a whole. A social-theoretical question that guided this research was: How has the management of an educational institution’s finances affected the accessibility of higher education? In this project I took into consideration how the distribution of college resources contributed to a student’s postsecondary experience. The empirical research questions guiding this project included: Is there a correlation between institutional spending and revenue, and student financial aid? Can similar correlations be found with spending, revenue, and student debt? Is there a correlation between student debt and cost of tuition, and completion and retention rates? Through my data analysis, I was able to determine that increased institution expenditures on student services increased rates of completion and retention. However, I was unable to find any clear indications of corporatization within the institutions. With this and the limitations of the scope of the data set, I was also unable to argue for or against any claim regarding financial management and accessibility.

I explored the college scorecard data published by the U.S. Department of Education (DOE). I used a subset of this data specific to California institutions and examined the rates of retention and completion of full-time, first time Title IV students. I explored the available financial categories of this dataset to attempt to find a correlation between them and the aforementioned rates of retention and completion. The relevant data used spanned from the years 2011 to 2017, the seven most recent years made available by the DOE. I chose to start at 2011 since it is the earliest year with the most modern variables and definitions. I focused more attention to the trends of public institutions: California State University (CSU) campuses, University of California (UC) campuses, community colleges, etc. I analyzed the trends of all California campuses, public and private, but specifically grouped the public campuses together as they are the more populated campuses and provided better data about the California postsecondary education system than private campuses.

News reports and individual criticism suggest that universities are becoming increasingly corporate, focusing more on profit than on education. Tuition costs have been on the rise over the last several years and paying for higher education is becoming more and more difficult. Large campuses like the UC campuses are admitting an increasing number of out of state and international students - the groups of students who pay the highest tuition - a sign to some that the administrators are trying to maximize profits. If true, this trend of corporatization of institutions creates a rift in the accessibility of higher education.

This topic is currently an important area of study because the demand for a college degree in the workplace is increasing and obtaining said degree is becoming more expensive. The rise in student expenses not only burdens current students but the prospective costs will also deter and prevent potential students from enrolling in higher education. College and higher education is becoming seemingly more and more inaccessible as the obligations become greater. It is important to see what areas contribute to inaccessibility and the effects of those areas on the student body. This research contributes to our understanding of the economics at play in the educational system and their correlation to educational accessibility.

Data Context and Historical Background

The College Scorecard Data is an online tool and data set provided by the United States Department of Education to allow the public access to quantifiable data about different colleges and universities. The data set provides historical data about campuses and their student body from the last twenty years. Though, it must be noted that the data collection is centralized around Title IV, or federal financial aid receiving, strudents. The data set itself and corresponding tool were not launched until 2015 under the Obama administration as a way to redefine how we compare colleges. Before the launch of the College Scorecard Data website, all college rankings were done by third parties like U.S. News and Princeton Review, who use ambiguous and inconsistent metrics for calculating the rankings (Zhou 2015). Using data from the Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System (IPEDS), National Student Loan Data System (NSLDS), and the Department of Treasury; the Department of Education aggregates the data together and publishes the federal data on their website.

There are currently no laws in place to mandate the collection, aggregation, and/or publication of data, however there is an executive order put in place by President Obama that accomplishes the same task. During the Obama administration, there was a big push toward open, transparent federal data for the public. This movement was named the Open Government Initiative. The mandates of the Open Government Initiative require government agencies to publish open, machine-readable data for public consumption. The IPEDS, NSLDS, and the Department of Treasury all fall under the jurisdiction of this executive order and because of this, their data was made open and the creation of the Scorecard was possible. Given the types of data that the College Scorecard wanted to make available, the Department of Education and the Department of Treasury had to share data between themselves in order to aggregate the data collected by each department individually into a single data set that would provide metrics of comparison for different postsecondary institutions.

Since the College Scorecard came during the time of the Open Government Initiative, there was an obligation, through executive order, for access to transparent, machine-readable federal data. The Obama administration wanted to provide reliable and accessible data on colleges so anyone would be able to compare colleges using features like graduation rates, tuition, and loan repayment. The IPEDS collects its data annually through surveys administered by the National Center for Education Statistics. Because of the Higher Education Act, institutions that participated in Title IV federal student aid programs are required to complete IPEDS questionnaires. The NSLDS collects its loan data from federal loan and grant information systems and also utilizes Free Application for Federal Student Aid information to collect student demographic information. The methods of data collection has not changed since the launch of the Scorecard, but the IPEDS has added more sections to its survey, like Outcome Measures, which provided more data on completion, transfers, and continued enrollment of full-time first-time students (“Documentation College Scorecard Data” 2019). The College Scorecard uses metrics derived from the annual reports of the IPEDS and NSLDS data to create their own annually updated data set of discrete data values, rather than ambiguous categories, that is a more reliable and accessible means of assessing affordability and value of colleges.

The data set is not without its flaws. The data set only represents a small subset of the total student body population due to the limitations of the group sampled for data collection. Focused on Title IV, undergraduate students, the data set a significant amount of the student population. Some estimates have a value of only about 50 percent of students represented (Rothwell 2015).

Structures, Patterns, and Anomalies

My data set is one that consists of rows that represent individual institutions, unique to the physical location of the campus, rather than institution name, for any given year. The columns in my particular data set are variables that describe different characteristics of an institution. Some of these can be related to the school as an entity like the name, its revenue and expenditures, and whether it’s a public, private for-profit, or private non-profit institution. Others are related to the students such as demographics, cost of attendance, and in- and out-of-state tuition.

One of the most notable missing values come from the column that represents share of Asian Pacific Islander undergraduate, degree-seeking students. For several years in the data set, that variable is null for every school in the dataset. Since it was unlikely that schools stopped reporting data for this particular demographic, I hypothesized that since the source data goes back so many years that the categorization of this demographic may have changed over time and that column was kept in the data set to preserve the historical data. Reading into the data dictionary, and the definitions of the different demographic variables and confirmed that the categorical definition of this demographic changed from Asian Pacific Islander to Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander.

A large amount of financial data was missing from my data set, from both public and private colleges. Both subsets of college types had entries within them that were missing some value, whether it be retention rates, default rates, and/or financial information like an institution’s spending and revenue. For private institutions, the percentage of values that were NA was higher than that of the public institutions. It is not possible to tell the cause of all these missing values with the data that I have. There is no way to verify the true meanings of these missing values. One possibility is could be a choice to refuse to disclose the information, but it could also be equally as likely that a given college does not have the data to release because they do not calculate for that given variable in the data set.

To both the private school and public school data sets that I made, I applied a mutate function call where I summed up the shares of all minority groups in each institution. I calculated the average share of minority undergraduates for all schools in a given data set for each year by calling summarize and taking the mean of the new column I created with the mutate call. As a result, I was able to see the average percentage minority students in each year and how the value changed over time. What this showed me is that share that minority students hold has been increasing in public schools and decreasing in private schools over time. This directly relates back to an issue in my research abstract regarding the accessibility of higher education. The percentage of minority students can be used as a metric for accessibility in my research project and can be potentially correlated with financial data.

ca_total <- ca_total %>% mutate(PCT_MIN = UGDS_BLACK+UGDS_HISP+UGDS_AIAN+UGDS_ASIAN+UGDS_NHPI+UGDS_2MOR)
ca_total <- ca_total %>% mutate(UGDS_MIN = PCT_MIN * UGDS)

By grouping the data by year and calling a summarize to get the average cost of attendance, average net cost, and average aid (obtained by subtracting net cost from cost of attendance) per year for all institutions in the public school data set. What this has shown me is that cost of attendance, net cost, and aid have all been increasing in recent years. Again, this can also relate back to the issue of accessibility of higher education. In this case, I could use the data to get a sense of change over time for each category and compare the rates of change for each of them. If one rate of change for one metric outpaces another, that could give me insight on the state of accessibility. For example, if cost rises faster than aid, then it could be said that school is becoming less accessible. We can further examine other variables to try to come to a similar insights on the topic of accessibility.

Variation

The first plot is a waffle chart. By calculating the number of each type of institution and putting it over the total number of institutions, we obtain the percentage share of each type of institution. By creating this waffle chart, we are able to visually represent the share of each type of California institution by control where each square represents a one percent share. From this, we can see that public institutions actually have the smallest share out of all institutions at around a 30 percent share. Since it is well known that the cost of private schools is, on average, higher than that of public schools, one could use this information and insight to make an argument about how private schools’ majority share affects the affordability and accessibility of higher education.

waffle(control, rows = 10, colors = c("salmon", "mediumpurple3", "mediumpurple4"), 
       title = "Share of Institutions by Control", xlab = "One Square = One Percent")

This plot was created by grouping the data by year and calculating the median revenue and expenses from the main data set. With this representation of the data, we can observe the change of spending and revenue over time, and we are able to compare the rates at which revenue and spending are changing and gather insights by the differences in the curves. What this plot demonstrates is that revenue has experienced substantial growth between 2011 and 2017. It also shows that expenses have also experienced similar rates of growth during this time. There might be some economics at play here in terms of why are they are growing at the rate they are, but there is nothing definitive.

This plot in particular shows that the two rates are growing at almost identical rates (around 15 percent). This tells me that the variables are behaving more or less normally and there is no outside variable working as an influence on them.

Additional Data and Insights

The data that I elected to join my primary data set to is the financial data from the Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System (IPEDS) surveys from the same scope as my primary data set. The data is collected and published annually. This data set is relevant to my research because it provides a more comprehensive revenue and expenditure data for the institutions in my primary data set. I have elected to join this data set with my primary data set since the IPEDS provides the data for both data sets so I can know what to expect from the new data set. This new finance data set also provides the additional data I was seeking to make more accurate analyses.

Data Issues

One issue that I have found with the accuracy with the data in the data set is that for some variables, the values within them seem so extreme that either they seem like they must be inaccurate or they are flat out, without a doubt, inaccurate. When analyzing all of the California institutions, filtering out rows where the variable representing the number of undergraduate, degree-seeking students is zero; I find that several institutions report this number. Some are just single-year stints, but others like the Southern California University of Health Sciences, report zero undergraduates multiple times. Though there are not many institutions that show this pattern, it shows that erroneous data can exist in the data set and it makes me wary of the accuracy of other variables. Any analysis must be done with some increasing degree of skepticism and many conclusions or interpretations will have inaccuracies. This makes it difficult since not all inaccuracies may be as blatant as zero undergraduate students.

My data set is inherently limited because it only represents the students that receive financial aid. Not only is the data set nonrepresentative, it is also incomplete. The incompleteness can be seen in two metrics that are important to my research: admission rate and retention rate. Plotting any graph using any of these two metrics would show that many missing values were removed. In more detail, by filtering out the NAs and calculating the percentage they accounted for, I found that in the collective California data set, almost 70% of all entries had missing retention rate values. A similar statistic is true with completion rates. This significantly decreases the sample size of my analyses and, in turn, the accuracy of the analyses. Insights become skewed when less than one third of the data available can be represented on a plot or can be used in a calculation. These limitations cause the conclusions made to be more reliant on assumptions that a smaller subset can accurately represent the whole. A similar issue is seen in student financial data. The data available is already limited in its representation of the student body so having the sample size shrunk even further makes the results of my research more skeptical. The sample size available is no where near enough for the scope of my research.

Another issue that I run into is the information gap between the data collectors and aggregators and myself as the data analyst. The creators of the main data set know what values of the other data sets were pulled from to create the aggregated value in the main data set. For example, the cost of attendance value in the main data set gets the values of tuition, fees, and book costs from other data sets to get the average value but I am unable to see the broken down values to see how each category affects the cost. The insights that I can make from data analysis are limited because I am unable to see whether the changes are caused by something institution controlled, like tuition, or something more out of the hands of the institution like the cost of books. Without the ability to see these broken down categories, it becomes more difficult for me to make correlations between costs and institutions’ financial management, the crux of my research.

Through the experience of my research, I will add that insights and analysis of the data set are prone to misinterpretation. Quick, inaccurate conclusions could be made from initial observations, but further insights often tell a different story. Several instances of Simpson’s paradox were found during my research and are highlighted in my Key Findings.

Key Findings

From the analyses performed on my data set, I have gathered enough insights to address the research questions I set out to answer. On the concern of potential institution corporatization, from 2011 to 2017, based on the median values over time, regardless of whether the focus is on public institutions or private institutions , there is no clear evidence that California post-secondary institutions’ revenues are significantly outpacing their expenditures meaning that there is no indication of attempts at maximizing income. However, it must be noted that the data present in the data set provides a high level view of institution finances and does not show where the money is moving to and from internally. The variables used for the previous insight refer to the median total revenue and expenditures, these values are calculated by summing up other values within the IPEDS Finances data set but even with these values, it is not entirely clear what transactions make up these data values. On the other hand, there seems to be a strong, clear correlation between retention and completion rates, and student services expenses in public institutions over the same period of time. The correlation coefficients for retention and completion with student services expenses are 0.69 and 0.75 respectively. Combined with the downward trend of median loan default rates and increased median values of service expenditures and financial aid, it appears that the management of finances is benefitting the students of public institutions but unfortunately, making such a conclusion would be making assumptions about the data.

By looking at adjusted completion and retention rate plots, we can see that Simpson’s paradox is present within them. Calculating the correlation coefficient on- and observing the data as a single showed us what seemed to be a strong, clear correlation between student services expenses and retention and completion rates. Yet, by distinguishing individual institutions, we can see that the trend does not necessarily hold true. This difference is especially clear when looking at the UC campuses.

g_legend <- function(a.gplot){ 
    tmp <- ggplot_gtable(ggplot_build(a.gplot)) 
    leg <- which(sapply(tmp$grobs, function(x) x$name) == "guide-box") 
    legend <- tmp$grobs[[leg]] 
    legend

Analyzing the change over time from 2011 to 2017, we can see that both the median values of cost of attendance and debt after graduation have each increased, in total, about 15 percent. Similarly to the other analyses, the values used and the insights made have inaccuracies given the limited subset of data that the analyses are based on and limited scope of the data set itself. It is very important to note that any calculations and analysis done on this data set will yield some inaccuracies given the incompleteness of the raw data.

This data set has major knowledge and information gaps that prevent me from conducting accurate analyses on the data and make it more difficult to answer my research questions. The collectors of this data are undoubtedly experts in their field. The reasoning behind aggregation of different values from different data sets and the values that they yield may make sense to them, but for an outside data analyst, it is not as clear. The documentation of the data set provides no breakdown of the individual values that make up an aggregated value, like cost of attendance, so I am left to make high level analyses, which will inherently result in more shallow insights and calculations. If I had access to these broken down values, I would be able to categorize the types of revenue and expenditures that an institution manages. With this, I would be able to see the percentage of institution revenue that originates from student payments (i.e. tuition and fees), and the percentage of institution expenditures that go towards the benefit of the student body (i.e. student services expenses). The ideal break-down would also show me data like the movement of revenue money so I would be able to make insights towards the potential corporatization of post-secondary education.

Additionally, I am unable to conduct more complete research and have a more complete understanding of my data domain because of the undone science within it. The College Scorecard provides a plethora of data for students going through the post-secondary education system, and correlations can be made among several variables within the data set. However, there is very little research, if any, done on the prospective side of post-secondary education. The data set can show the effects on an institution’s financial management on current students and, to some degree, graduates, but there is no way to tell how the same information affects prospective students. Research on the correlation between costs and other financial factors; and their impact on the pursuit of post-secondary education by prospective students are left undone and knowledge is left unproduced.

Conclusion and Further Research

Through the research and analysis I did for this project, I was able to advance my knowledge on the topics related to institution finance management and their correlation with variables within my data set like retention rates, completion rates, and debt. Though I was able to successfully find correlations in the areas of my empirical questions, based on the data and methods that I used, I have only scratched the surface of the analysis and insights of the social-theoretical question that I had posed as motivation for this project. Both the revenue and expenditures of institutions show comparable rates of growth from 2011 and 2017 and show us the possibility of the economics at play in the education system. Yet, the analyses performed only give a surface level view of a single perspective of the management and administration of the system. More research and analysis must be performed in order to progress the understanding of story within the data.

I must commend the availability, timeliness, and the relevance of the data sets I used. The websites that host the data are easy to find, easy to navigate, and the data ready to download in CSV format. The main data set, and the data sets it depends on, update on a regular basis, usually annually. The data provided in the education domain is relevant, but it lacks in exhaustiveness, completeness, and to some degree, accuracy. I had hundreds of variables to choose from, but for many institutions, the variables’ values were null and the subset that the data collectors sampled from prevented an accurate representation of the entire California student body. For a data set with aggregated values like the one I used, seeing the high level, aggregated overview of the values limits how much one could understand about the composition of the data, and that could make a difference in the analysis.

Though the data sets used were useful but there are still several improvements that can be made and suggests the data collectors can field. The biggest improvement that I hope can be made is the completeness of the data sets. For the College Scorecard, somehow collecting data from non-Title IV students would greatly increase the completeness of the data set representationally and improve the accuracy of any analyses made using the data. A suggestion that I would like to give to the data collectors is to change the organization of the data dictionary so it is easier to find the source of a certain data value, specifically regarding IPEDS data. I found it difficult to find which IPEDS data set certain values came from and I would have liked an individual column stating the source data set rather than that information being in the middle of a chunk of text in the notes section.

Further questions that I would like to explore as a result from work on this research are: “How are prospective students (i.e high school) affected by institutions’ financial management?” and “Do the same patterns of correlation present for traditional students exist for non-traditional students as well?” A majority of the data is sampled from full-time, first-time students in the postsecondary education system and is not representative of non-traditional students at all. I would like to explore the similarities and differences between traditional and non-traditional students by conducting the same analysis I did in my research on both groups. I also would like to find out how finances play a role in preventing people from pursuing higher education.

Despite the issues with completeness and representation of my data and analysis, I was still able to produce meaningful insights. Specifically, my research gave me a lot of insight about traditional students in the college system, but there are still many questions to answer about prospective and non-traditional students. I hope, with further research in this domain, that progress can be made to understanding these two groups.

Throughout this report, I have highlighted the pitfalls of this data set and the obstacles that I encountered as a result of those pitfalls. This is a high quality data set, but it was not quite satisfactory for the aims of my research. Needless to say, it is vital to understand that the pitfalls of the data set are specific to my research. The College Scorecard is a well-structured, well-maintained, information-rich data set that is readily available to the public. The issues that I encountered were rooted in an issue of the scope of my research rather than the data set used. The data set is simply not designed for a scope as large as my research goals. I will also have to note that there exists several other IPEDS data sets that could have supplemented my working data set and helped address issues of accuracy and representation I had through the research process. Unfortunately due to time constraints, I was unable to incorporate these extra data sets into my research.
